<TEXT>
a soviet newspaper has provided new details about 
dictator josef stalins death which has been shrouded in mystery 
because of incomplete or disputed official accounts 
sovietskaya estonia quotes a retired bodyguard as saying stalin 
went unattended for at least 14 hours after suffering a stroke 
because lavrenti beria the head of the secret police refused to 
let anyone summon physicians 
the article appeared in sundays edition of the newspaper 
published in the soviet republic of estonia and copies arrived in 
moscow on tuesday 
the paper attributed most of its report to the bodyguard maj 
at rykov who it said was present when stalin stricken at his 
dacha outside moscow died in march 1953 
rykov told the paper that beria insisted stalin was only 
sleeping and his guards panicked when they found the dictator 
unconscious on the floor of his country residence or dacha 
no one dared contradict beria who became chief of the secret 
police in 1938 and carried out bloody purges and stalin was not 
attended by doctors until the next day according to the report 
stalin had ruled the country since 1924 eliminating his 
opponents inside and outside the ruling communist party and 
enforcing harsh collectivization 
little official information was given about his death and 
historians have challenged the official reports released as other 
party officials engaged in a power struggle for leadership 
sovietskaya estonia basing its article on what it said was a 
lengthy interview with rykov gave this version 
stalin probably died several days before march 5 1953 the day 
given officially as the date of death 
he died at his dacha and not in the kremlin as official 
reports said 
an autopsy showed stalin suffered a series of small strokes in 
his final years that affected parts of the brain responsible for 
psychotic activities results of the autopsy have not been 
officially released 
it took more than six months to embalm and preserve the body 
before it was put on public display 
the newspaper said rykov had served as a guard at stalins dacha 
and recently entered the papers editorial department and offered 
to tell his story 
he could talk for hours about the leader of the people 
saving every little fact in his memory the report said 
it quoted rykov was as saying stalin went to bed at 4 am on 
march 1 1953 after guests had left 
in the afternoon guards noticed there was no movement in 
stalins study or other rooms but at 630 pm a light was turned 
on in the study and in the hall rykov said according to the 
newspaper 
it quoted him as saying no one summoned the guards who became 
concerned and when one went in to deliver a letter stalin was 
lying on the carpet in the dining room having obvious 
difficulties in saying anything other guards came into the room 
and carried stalin into the largest hall it could be seen that he 
was cold and he probably was on the floor three to four hours 
without any help 
the account said beria and georgi m malenkov a close aide who 
briefly succeeded stalin as the communist party leader arrived at 
3 am on march 2 after beria telephoned instructions that no one 
was to say anything about stalins condition 
after seeing the unconscious leader beria insisted the guards 
had panicked and that stalin was simply sleeping according to 
the report 
doctors finally were summoned apparently by nikita s 
khrushchev who won the power struggle to become the party chief 
later in 1953 and they arrived between 9 am and 10 am 
the doctors were so nervous they could not even take off 
stalins shirt rykov was quoted as saying it had to be cut 
through with scissors the diagnosis was brain hemorrhage 
treatment was attempted but it was not surgical what surgeon 
could take responsibility for stalins life especially when beria 
frightened everybody asking whether they could guarantee that 
stalins life could be preserved 
beria was arrested in july 1953 and charged with conspiracy 
against the state after a secret trial he and six alleged 
accomplices where shot in december 1953 
the newspaper article also described the evening of march 5 
1953 when ss debov who had embalmed the body of soviet founder 
vladimir lenin was summoned 
one of stalins cars took debov to stalins postmortem 
examination which showed some irreversible changes localized in 
parts of the brain responsible for psychotic activities which were 
caused by a number of small hemorrhages rykov said 
stalins funeral was held on march 9 and the body carried to the 
mausoleum which was closed for more than eight months for a 
permanent embalming procedure 
on nov 17 1953 the mausoleum was opened for the people with 
lenin and stalin lying together the newspaper said 
it reported the identical coffins remained side by side until 
oct 31 1961 when soldiers took stalins remains to a plain 
gravesite nearby but outside the kremlin wall 
khrushchev had begun his campaign against what he called the 
cult of stalin 
