rival factions in tehran have disputed postwar policies 
particularly the task of reconstruction and efforts by parliament 
speaker hashemi rafsanjani to bring iran out of political isolation 
rafsanjani the acting military commander and the most powerful 
figure in iran after khomeini and khamenei favor seeking foreign 
investment to help rebuild the countrys shattered economy 
musavi a radical technocrat who has been premier for seven 
years opposes outside intervention he fears it will drive iran 
into debt and allow in the multinationals booted out after the 1979 
revolution 
philip robbins of the londonbased royal institute for 
international affairs said it was easy enough to decide during 
the war not to take loans from the west when no one was offering 
them anyway 
but now western companies are willing to do business with 
iran that presents the iranians with some difficult decisions 
he said in a telephone interview 
musavi despite impeccable revolutionary credentials has no 
power base of his own like rafsanjani khamenei and interior 
minister ali akbar mohtashemi a hardliner whose influence is 
growing 
irans internal divisions were sharpened when khomeini decided 
last month to accept a unsponsored ceasefire in the war with 
iraq after a string of battlefield defeats 
musavi won a personal vote of confidence in parliament in july 
squelching speculation that he might be eased out and replaced 
possibly by mohtashemi 
but the political feuding probably will come to a head by next 
year when khameneis term as president expires analysts said 
khomeini has decreed khamenei cannot run again 
the debate over irans direction in the postwar era is only part 
of the power struggle between rival factions over who will fill the 
political vacuum when khomeini dies 
the 88yearold revolutionary leader reportedly has been ailing 
iranian leaders have denied that but khomeini has appeared 
increasingly frail in recent public appearances 
