the pentagon is continuing to pay tens of 
millions of dollars more than it should for weapons because defense 
contractors are hiding information that would bring prices down 
the general accounting office said wednesday 
despite some pentagon successes in halting overpriced weapons 
contractors still arent complying with a 1962 law designed to 
provide more information to government contract negotiators the 
congressional watchdog agency told a house subcommittee 
the law the truth in negotiations act requires disclosure to 
the government by contractors of all relevant information about 
contracts companies found to be in violation can be sued for 
recovery of the overpricing 
our work shows that when contractors fail to disclose relevant 
cost or pricing data the government pays higher contract prices 
than warranted said paul math associate director of the gaos 
national security division 
math told the house government operations national security 
subcommittee that gao auditors have looked at 18 major contractors 
in the past four years and recommended that 32 million be 
recovered on 38 contractrs 
the pentagon agreed and has recovered 6 million and is still 
trying to get the rest of the money back math said 
a new round of gao checks on five contractors found potential 
overpricing of almost 18 million math said about 13 million was 
due to noncompliance with the 1962 law and the other 5 million 
was attributed to faulty contractor estimate systems 
the reviews involve noncompetitive contracts which are awarded 
without bidding the pentagon has generally pushed for more 
competition in its contracts in recent years but still awarded 79 
billion worth of noncompetitive contracts in fiscal 1987 math 
said 
the pentagon embarrassed by overpriced weapons has instituted 
a series of reforms that have partially solved the problem math 
said 
