<TEXT>
members of congress expressed concern 
wednesday that americas electronics industry could suffer 
irreparably if it is left behind in the race to develop a new 
highquality television system 
the result they said could cost the country in many ways an 
even higher trade deficit and thousands of jobs lost as well as 
the loss of potential military medical consumer and other 
applications that are expected to come with development of the 
technology 
rep edward j markey dmass chairman of the 
telecommunications subcommittee asked electronics industry trade 
associations to submit reports to the panel by january outlining 
steps the government could take to assure american involvement in 
highdefinition tv 
suggestions have ranged from antitrust exemptions for us 
companies involved in hdtv research and development to 
appropriating pentagon funds for hdtv research because of the 
potential military applications of the technology he said 
over the last decade the united states has shifted from a major 
supplier to a net importer of electronics products he noted 
hdtv could make a bad situation worse markey said at the 
final of three hearings on highdefinition tv called hdtv 
high definition tv produces clearer brighter images on a wider 
tv screen with highquality sound the japanese have been 
developing hdtv for nearly 20 years and the europeans have been 
working on their own system for several years both systems are 
incompatible with us television broadcasting 
the federal communications commission last week set preliminary 
guidelines that will allow research to proceed toward establishing 
an american hdtv system under the fcc guidelines a us system 
must be able to be received on existing tv sets so current 
equipment would not become obsolete but to receive improved 
picture quality viewers would have to buy a new tv set 
richard elkus jr chairman of the prometrix corp and 
testifying for the american electronics association said advanced 
tv offers the us electronics industry an opportunity to rebound 
in a market projected to reach 20 billion in us sales and 40 
billion worldwide by the year 2007 
it also will have ripple effects in other areas he said for 
example hdtv products will use a large supply of advanced 
semiconductors and hdtv will have applications in military and 
medical fields he said in testimony submitted to the panel 
he added however that regardless of what standard the united 
states selects it wont stop the japanese from entering the us 
market 
more important than selecting a standard he said is government 
and industry coming up with a strategy to put american companies 
back on the electronics manufacturing track and to develop 
marketing and distribition systems that will rival the japanese 
about 20 advancedtv systems are under development and competing 
to be designated as the us hdtv standard 
