<TEXT>
a century of misguided attempts to fight every 
forest fire worsened this summers blazes in yellowstone national 
park by allowing a natural buildup of fuel national park service 
officials said wednesday 
its obvious it made it worse said walt dabney chief 
ranger of the service 
if more fires of the past had been allowed to burn fewer 
combustible gases would have built up through the natural decaying 
of tree leaves and underbrush thus todays forest blazes would be 
easier to manage the officials said 
though the service will review its policy of letting many fires 
burn our policy is sound based on scientific research said 
william penn mott director of the service 
the problem is the building up of fuel in many areas due to 
the previous policy 
the park service has followed a policy of letting most fires 
burn since 1972 it fights them only when they threaten settled 
areas or areas outside the parks yellowstone was established as a 
park in 1872 
ecologists say natural fires are important in preserving species 
diversity and attracting wildlife in fact many species such as 
the lodgepole pine typical of yellowstone depend on fire for 
reproduction 
the forest service whose land almost completely surrounds 
yellowstone follows a similar policy for its wilderness areas 
but it relies on deliberate controlled burning and timber 
harvesting to manage the fifthsixths of its domain that is not 
wilderness in that larger area most fires are fought if the 
service judges that they will not stay within reasonable 
bounds said peterson 
since july 21 the park service has been trying to put out the 
fires in yellowstone and has directed its other installations to 
extinguish quickly any fire for which there wont be resources to 
monitor and steer away from vulnerable areas it has banned 
controlled burning for the rest of the summer 
of the 13 separate fire outbreaks in and near yellowstone five 
originally were allowed to burn some of them starting on forest 
service land outside the park some fires have merged leaving 
eight active now 
in hindsight we would have tried to put out every fire 
peterson said if we had known the weather would evolve the way 
it did we would have done it differently mott said 
without a crystal ball or higher connections that we dont 
have we cant know its not going to rain in july and august 
dabney said 
he said the current western fires are on a scale not seen for 
more than 200 years 
on capitol hill senators from wyoming and montana complained to 
interior secretary donald hodel that allowing some of the 
yellowstone fires to burn was a grave mistake they said mott 
should be fired because of the yellowstone destruction 
the national park service and the forest service made a very 
gross error in judgement naively and stupidly said max baucus 
dmont theres been too much hope and prayer and not enough 
action 
