<TEXT>
how do you undo a stalemate that is the 
question one whose answer eludes our most skilled politicians 
more accurately the nations political leaders evade the issue 
the result being that the job of straightening out americans 
finances is sort of a political ghost felt and even talked about 
but never confronted 
the problem is this how do you deal with the fact that 
americans want their social benefits such as social security and 
unemployment payments but are just as certain that they dont want 
taxes raised 
the conference board a businessfinanced research group that 
contracted for a survey on the subject in an effort to puncture the 
quandary came full circle with this conclusion 
while it is widely agreed that the federal deficit should be 
significantly reduced a formidable majority of americans continue 
to oppose any reductions in this nations social programs 
not all social programs are enthusiastically supported said 
fabian linden of the nonprofit board but those that are 
enthusiastically supported he found tend to be in the bigbucks 
area 
based on results from 5000 households surveyors found four of 
five oppose any cuts in social security medicare and veterans 
benefits and three in five oppose reductions in health research 
unemployment and childcare benefits 
the areas favored for reduction involved a far smaller 
percentage of the population only onethird for example said no 
cuts should be permitted in food stamps public housing welfare 
and aid to small businesses 
the most enthusiasm for cutting was in the foreign aid category 
with 61 percent more than double the percentage in any other 
category recommending large cuts and only 66 percent holding 
fast for no cuts 
more than 50 percent insisted there be no cuts for environmental 
protection and 46 percent held out for no cuts whatever in roads 
and highways spending 
the findings suggest americans are no nearer than before to 
solving the dilemma of wanting to spend more than to pay since one 
survey after another finds voters opposed to higher taxes 
the trick may be to find tax increases that affect the fewest 
number of people but such taxes of course are also likely to 
provide the least revenue among the possibilities therefore are 
taxes on cigarettes and alcohol 
perhaps the least likely tax to be accepted by the public would 
be the valueadded tax which as might be surmised is also the tax 
that could do most to correct the budget imbalance 
such a tax on the increase in value of products at the various 
stages in production and distribution might provide as much as 
127 billion in revenue compared to 4 billion to 8 billion for 
boosts in alcohol and cigarette taxes according to the 
congressional budget office 
some of the possibilities studied by the budget office would 
seem to have little chance of passing including taxing capital 
gains at death limiting mortgageinterest deductions and raising 
capital gains taxes on home sales 
somewhere there is a solution but it is deep in the dark 
confines of the political closet a spooky place where timid 
political candidates do not even want to look 
</TEXT>
