<TEXT>
market pessimism about opecs ability to 
restrain its production has pushed oil futures prices to nearly a 
twoyear low but experts say american drivers should see little 
benefit at the gas pump because of strong demand for the refined 
product 
on the new york mercantile exchange today the october contract 
for delivery of west texas intermediate the benchmark grade of 
us crude was down 9 cents a barrel at 1415 at late morning 
the contract dropped 55 cents a barrel on tuesday crude prices 
have not traded that low on the exchange since october 1986 when 
they reached 1373 per barrel 
responding to the drop several major us oil companies 
announced tuesday and today that they were cutting the official 
price they pay for west texas intermediate in the spot market 
futures contracts for refined oil products traded on the 
exchange also continued tuesdays decline wholesale unleaded 
gasoline for october delivery had fallen 033 cent a gallon to 
4220 cents at late morning while wholesale heating oil for 
october was down 023 cent at 4148 
the markets skepticism about the ability of the 13nation 
organization of petroleum exporting countries to trim its output 
has deepened in recent days after initial optimism about 
cooperation within the cartel resulting from the ceasefire between 
members iran and iraq 
opec secretarygeneral subroto recently capped off a series of 
meetings with oil producers by visiting officials in iran and iraq 
and tried to persuade iran to allow iraq a higher production quota 
but subroto made little headway in his efforts to win cooperation 
among opec members for curbing overall output 
there just doesnt seem to be any hope right now said linda 
