<TEXT>
industrial designer j gordon 
lippincott says he and his wife of 51 years edith often play a 
game when they travel abroad 
on the way in from the airport they see how quickly they can 
spot some corporate symbol that lippincott had a hand in designing 
the game seldom takes very long 
the lanky 79yearold lippincott who left the consulting firm 
that still bears his name 20 years ago for an assortment of other 
pursuits says he had a hand in developing symbols known the world 
over for companies such as cocacola co american express co 
general mills inc and campbell soup co 
but these days lippincott recalls his firms work on a car that 
has all but disappeared from the landscape his company helped with 
the styling of the tucker automobile 41 years ago only about 50 of 
the models were ever built 
lippincotts role in the project surfaced as attention has been 
drawn to the cars by the recentlyreleased movie tucker the man 
and his dream 
lippincott said his firm was about 4 years old when the aspiring 
automaker preston tucker stopped by one morning in 1947 tucker 
wanted a professional design firm to help him style an auto for 
the future one that had an engine in the rear and safety 
features like seat belts and popout windows and could travel 120 
miles per hour 
i didnt let on at first but wow did we ever lippincott 
recalled recently as visitors pored over the scrapbooks he keeps at 
the modern breezy house he built 16 years ago on a 40acre estate 
beside the farm river 
in those days every designer wanted to design a car he said 
the movie recounts how tucker developed the car and his travails 
with the securities and exchange commission over how he financed it 
the movie makes no reference to outside designers but 
lippincott said he doesnt mind he liked the movie adding that 
actor jeff bridges did a good job of capturing tuckers spirit 
in playing tucker in the movie 
lippincott said tucker already had a good idea of what he wanted 
to do by the time he came by for help he said tuckers chief 
designer alex tremulis had drawings and a small scalemodel of 
what the car would look like 
it included a front headlamp that swiveled as the wheels were 
turned 
lippincott said tucker wanted some advice from a design firm on 
the outer styling of the car he said he never knew precisely what 
led tucker to the firms midtown new york offices 
tucker showed up alone he brought no drawings of the car on 
which a lot of work had already been done he had no appointment 
but lippincott saw him anyway and liked his brashness his 
selfassurance his energy 
he was an immensely likable and persuasive person 
lippincott said 
lippincotts partner walter margulies insisted on being paid 
every week in advance and tucker agreed the decision meant the 
firm was one of the few associated with the automobile that made 
money from the venture tucker lost more than 20 million making 
the cars 
lippincott sent half of the offices 10 designers hal 
bergstrom phil egan read viemeister bud steinhilber and tucker 
madawick to chicago to work on the project they created a 
fullscale clay model in nine weeks beside another fullscale model 
tremulis was working on himself 
once the models were finished lippincott said it was left to 
tucker and tremulis to assemble the prototype and the cars 
themselves lippincotts involvement was over 
there is some disagreement about the extent of the lippincott 
contribution to the final version 
lippincott said his teams contribution is evident in the 
styling in the both the front and back of the car but conceded it 
is hard to pinpoint responsibility when many designers have a hand 
in a project 
tremulis who lives in california said the design team was good 
but that the car was 95 percent complete before the outside team 
began working on it 
egan who was part of the lippincott team and later returned to 
work for tremulis on interior design said from his home in 
california that tremulis deserves most of the credit for the car 
design but said the front and back of the car reflect the 
lippincott teams work 
lippincotts design advice was avidly sought by companies 
ranging from flashlight producers to steelmaking giants he helped 
chrysler corp with a corporate logo years later he sold his 
interest in lippincott amp margulies in the late 1960s 
he said he learned his most important design lesson in the 
mid40s when the bacardi rum makers asked his firm to redesign 
their label 
the firm proposed a festive approach that used a different color 
for each letter of the name 
lippincott said family politely listened to the presentation 
but offered no response pressed for a reaction the head of the 
family said it had been most helpful 
we have gone to the best package designer in the united 
states and you have confirmed my belief that we should not change 
our label the man said 
lippincott said the lesson was clear and he never forgot it 
when you have an entrenched brand identity proceed with great 
caution 
</TEXT>
