bill ramage a labor economist at the state labor department in 
rochester hes been following the rochester economy since 1978 
he said the areas manufacturers have stopped tightening their 
belts and trimming work forces partly because of the weak dollar 
and the areas service sector continues to grow 
kodak rochesters largest employer by far offers a good 
illustration of how the value of the dollar can affect main street 
usa 
when the dollar began to rise in the early part of this decade 
kodaks profits were pared by lost pennies and then nickels and 
then dimes on nearly every roll of film it sold overseas 
the dollars rise meant kodak would have to charge more money 
for its products in foreign markets in order to make the same 
profit but raising prices in yen marks or pounds would send 
customers away from kodak film to competitors brands 
so in an effort to hang onto its customers kodak didnt raise 
prices and hoped the dollar wouldnt keep getting stronger and keep 
costing the company money 
from 1981 into early 86 we estimate that we lost 4 billion 
in profits said kodak spokesman henry kaska 
in addition the company was forced to lay off more than 10000 
employees nearly half of them in rochester and suffer the first 
quarterly financial loss in company history 
the cutbacks were difficult for this city to cope with 
especially since rochesters conventional wisdom included thata 
job at kodak was a job for life 
but in 1986 the dollar began to fall and kodak began making 
more money from its overseas sales simply converting foreign 
profits into dollars at more favorable exchange rates meant 90 
million in extra profits in 1986 195 million in 1987 and a 
projected 260 million this year if the dollar remains at its 
current level 
