<TEXT>
the washington public power supply system 
fraud trial opened wednesday with lawyers making lastminute 
motions before thursdays planned start of jury selection 
the proceedings gave some idea of what could become important 
arguments in the giant civil case 
attorney kenneth kieffer representing some of the defendants 
said wppss operated in a fish bowl of publicity in the 1970s and 
it therefore would have been difficult or impossible for his 
clients to commit fraud 
but attorney paul bernstein of new york representing thousands 
of claimants in the class action lawsuit said that while some 
wppss meetings were open to the public and the media other 
gatherings of utility officials were regularly closed making fraud 
indeed possible 
to say the supply system operated in a fish bowl is not 
true bernstein told us district judge william browning 
wppss had signed a contract with 88 utilities to build two 
nuclear power plants but the plants were terminated when they were 
partially built and the subsequent 1983 default on 225 billion 
in bonds issued to finance the project was the biggest in the 
history of the municipal bond market 
wednesdays arguments came during discussions on what 
information should be presented to jurors to help them understand 
the complicated case 
the wppss case was shifted for trial from washington state to 
tucson following arguments that jurors from the northwest might be 
prejudiced because of the possibility they would pay for an 
eventual jury award through their electricity rates 
in the case more than 24000 people who bought bonds on the two 
plants have filed suit alleging there was fraud in planning and 
construction of the plants 
named as defendants were wppss its member utilities the 88 
participating utilities bond underwriters and engineering and 
financial advice firms 
settlements totaling 351 million to date have left among the 
defendants only 20 washington utilities one oregon utility two 
engineering firms and a company that gave financial advice to wppss 
the default occurred after energy projections for the northwest 
showed the electrical output of the partiallybuilt plants wppss 
nos 4 and 5 was more than the region needed 
the plants were terminated in january 1982 and default came in 
1983 after the washington supreme court ruled most of the 88 
utilities investing in the projects had signed illegal contracts 
with wppss 
wednesday the defense argued unsuccessfully that the judges 
rules for trial would result in a playing field tilted in favor 
of plaintiffs 
youve put the hammer the firing mechanism in plaintiffs 
hands kieffer said in arguing that plaintiffs would be able to 
control the trial 
keiffer said he feared the defense would be unable to put its 
case in front of the jury in a logical manner if plaintiffs have 
the ability to set the order in which witnesses will appear 
jury selection is expected to take two days browning has 
ordered that 20 jurors be seated in the federal multidistrict 
litigation which could last more than a year 
because it is a civil case only six jurors eventually may be 
called upon to issue a verdict 
wppss attempted to build five nuclear power plants in the 1970s 
to serve northwest customers of those one plant wppss no 2 at 
the hanford nuclear reservation is operating 
two others wppss nos 1 and 3 were mothballed under 
construction delays five years ago 
bonds sold to build those three plants are paid for through the 
bonneville power administration but the terminated plants nos 4 
and 5 never enjoyed bpa protection 
