<DOCNO> AP880907-0284 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the wealthy hunt brothers moved a step closer 
toward removing their key businesses from from bankruptcy 
proceedings wednesday by signing a nearly 780 million plan to end 
their twoyear legal battle with creditor banks over penrod 
drilling co 
under the agreement the hunts nelson bunker william herbert 
and lamar and trusts they control will convey numerous tracts of 
real estate to the banks in consideration for forgiveness of 200 
million in existing debt 
in addition a newly restructured loan to penrod in the amount 
of 525 million will be secured by notes and penrod assets and the 
restructured company will make a cash payment of 538 million 
the banks will control for the hunt trusts all of penrods 
stock with 50 percent of the shares held for the banks themselves 
while the trusts will retain the right to redeem all the stock held 
for the banks at a predetermined price 
the agreement ends months of sometimes heated negotiations 
over the future of penrod according to a statement by hunt 
energy 
penrod the worlds biggest independent offshore oildrilling 
company and its sister company placid oil sued 23 of their lenders 
for fraud and misrepresentation in 1986 after defaulting on 15 
billion in bank loans two of the banks since have been dropped 
from the case 
the suit sought 14 million in damages alleging the banks one 
group of which had sued to recover 760 million in past due loans 
to penrod conspired to drive penrod and placid out of business by 
forcing them to agree to an unreasonable payment schedule while 
offering their competitors more favorable terms 
in august 1986 the trust estates of william herbert nelson 
bunker and lamar hunt filed for chapter 11 bankruptcy protection 
for the trust partnership that owns penrod drilling penrod itself 
was not under bankruptcy court protection 
all parties to the penrod agreement penrod officers bank 
representatives and hunt estate trustees were on hand wednesday in 
new york to sign documents executing the plan the documents will 
be held in escrow pending approval of the plan to reorganize the 
three trust estates that own penrod 
judge harold abramson has scheduled hearings to begin thursday 
in federal bankruptcy court in dallas 
calls placed wednesday night to hunt officials by the associated 
press were not immediately returned 
penrods current management and field personnel will remain in 
place according to marshall ballard general manager of penrod 
last month a federal jury decided the hunt brothers must pay 
over 130 million in damages for conspiring to corner the world 
silver market in the late 1970s thereby ruining the investments of 
minpeco sa the peruvian governments mineral marketing company 
</TEXT>
